# ESXi lab Setup


Because I wanted a lab to build tools, test my skills, and learn from both the offensive and defensive sides of technology, I set up a free VMWare ESXi host to house all of my VMs.


## ESXi installation


Sadly I didn't take any screenshots of the installation, but it was pretty straightforward. I downloaded the ISO on to a flash drive, and booted my host machine up with the flash drive plugged in. A few options and clicks later, I had my lab host!


## Setting up ESXi


I wanted my VMs to live on two different VLANs so I could isolate the ones I expected to use for building / testing from the ones I expected to make the "victims" of my security testing. I started by ensuring that both NICs for my host were connected to my Unifi switch, and the port profiles were set to the two VLANs I intended to use for the lab.


After that, I had to play around with some ESXi options to get the guest VMs the way I wanted them. I started bu adding a virtual switch that was connected to VMNIC1 (my second physical NIC, as the first was being used by the "normal" ESXi management and VM network).


Then I created a new port group for my victim VMs and assigned that to the newly created virtual switch.


Last (and maybe not necessarily - the jury is still out) I created a second VMKernel NIC and another new port group that I called the "Alt Management Network" set to the new virtual switch. This made the second virtual switch look pretty much exactly the same as the original one.



## Configuring the virtual machines (VLAN1)


On my "normal" ESXi network, I wanted a few VMs: Kali Linux for offensive security, Ubuntu for general development, and a Windows 10 machine with no security applied (which would serve as my "way in" to the other network). 

### Ubuntu


I installed Ubuntu and made quick work of the setup, installing:

- vscode
- pycharm
- git
- curl
- rust
- build-essential
- mingw-w64
- samba

I cloned a few repos of mine to the machine, and set up a samba share so I could easily move tools around.

### Kali

After installing Kali I cloned the following repos that I had used in the past and knew I would want again:

- evil-winrm
- BloodHound
- linux-smart-enumeration
- mimikatz
- RsaCtfTool

Then I installed a few packages that I also wanted:

- feroxbuster
- joplin

Last, a few usablility tasks:

- set up a VPN connection to connect to HackTheBox (one of the things I use for practice)
- [added the BurpSuite cert to Firefox](https://portswigger.net/burp/documentation/desktop/external-browser-config/certificate/ca-cert-firefox)
- added Foxyproxy to Firefox, and made two SOCK5 proxies - one for BurpSuite and one for SSH tunneling
- changed the terminal transparenct to 0 for documentating screenshots
- set the VM to connect to the Ubuntu VM's samba share on boot


### Windows 10


When setting up the Windows machine, I tried as much as possible not to use the built-in online account things that Microsoft tries to get you to. Nothing wrong with them, but they aren't my thing.


The hardest part was turning off all the security features, with the most annoying being [disabling real-time protection for good, which I eventually did via a Registry key](https://www.tenforums.com/tutorials/3569-turn-off-real-time-protection-microsoft-defender-antivirus.html#option6).


I also installed Visual Studio, an offline version of Miscrosoft Office I bought for ~$25, and made a shortcut to the Ubuntu machine's samba share.


## Configuring the virtual machines (VLAN2)


Now that it was configure the victim / vulnerable VMs, I took the easy way out on the first machine and just added a second network adapter to the Windows 10 VM and put it on the port group I had created for the second virtual switch.


Then I created 3 Windows Server VMs:

- 2022 to act as a Domain Controller
- 2022 to be a server on the domain
- 2019 to be another server on the domain


After configuring a domain and adding the two servers to it, I created two more Windows 10 machines and added them to the domain.


Last, I created five domain user accounts. Most of them had pretty good passwords, but one has a very easily-cracked password. These accounts and machines on my domain serve as a great place for me to learn about the security of computers in a domain.
